aches have relied on structural perspectives, attributing the problem of violence to Latin America's colonial past or its conflictual contemporary politics. Bringing together scholars and practitioners, this volume argues that violence is often rooted more in contingent outcomes than in deeply embedded structures. Addressing topics ranging from the root sources of violence in Haiti to kidnapping in Colombia, from the role of property rights in patterns of violence to the challenges of peacebuilding, The Politics of Violence in Latin America is an essential step towards understanding the causes and contexts of violence-and changing the mechanisms that produce it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh  aBrazil.  aCaribbean.  aChile.  aColombia.  aHaiti.  aLatin American war.  aMexio.  aViolence.  acivil war.  acolonial violence.  acontingent perspectives.  akidnapping.  amurder.  apeacemaking.  astate violence.  astructural perspectives.  astructural violence.  aviolent crime.  aviolent kidnapping.1 aBonner, Michelle D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonner, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldmann, Andreas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuterrez Sanin, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcSherry, J. Patrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPereira, Anthony W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiccato, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoliczer, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoliczer, Pablo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.g